snippet.textDisplay: Ford is still pretty cut and dry when it comes to selling performance to trim packages. Though, I'd agree that they shouldn't brand soccer mom vehicles. Let's face it though. I'm old. Sometimes it's a matter of compromise when you hit the lot. Momma wants something practical, and dad wants something with a little bite. That's why a Edge or Explorer ST is a thing. However, as long as they continue to make performance versions of already impressive sports cars, pick-ups and honestly...standard economy cars like the focus and fiesta...which are baseline, extremely underwhelming...can you blame them for trying to create new markets? Failed to even mention the Taurus SHO. Failed to mention that Quatro is just all-wheel drive, not a performance brand. Sure you can still buy a Type R, but for the price, You are universally better off with a Focus. Hell. I'd even argue that with the price differential, you could tune a Veloster. This video comes at a time, when our Baseline Mustangs and Camaros are putting out 300hp. I get this is a sentimental piece, but it's somewhat incorrect and 10 years behind. For price to performance, those Euro/Japanese brands can't keep up with what we are doing domestically. I don't count Dodge, because it's owned by Fiat. They have some interesting packages for the Charger/Challenger but with the exception of the Hellcat and that one dude that bought a Demon, they are incremental improvements over the SRT branding. However, they suffer reliability issues. So. Yeah.
snippet.textOriginal: Ford is still pretty cut and dry when it comes to selling performance to trim packages. Though, I'd agree that they shouldn't brand soccer mom vehicles. Let's face it though. I'm old. Sometimes it's a matter of compromise when you hit the lot. Momma wants something practical, and dad wants something with a little bite. That's why a Edge or Explorer ST is a thing. However, as long as they continue to make performance versions of already impressive sports cars, pick-ups and honestly...standard economy cars like the focus and fiesta...which are baseline, extremely underwhelming...can you blame them for trying to create new markets? Failed to even mention the Taurus SHO. Failed to mention that Quatro is just all-wheel drive, not a performance brand. Sure you can still buy a Type R, but for the price, You are universally better off with a Focus. Hell. I'd even argue that with the price differential, you could tune a Veloster.
